s very well (calmness), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (technical). Weaknesses: grumpy, uncooperative (teamwork). No mention of decision-making speed, leadership, professional development.\n\nC:\n- Strengths: can make correct decisions quickly (decision-making), known 100% reliable (reliability), creates positive atmosphere with crew (teamwork), can make correct decisions quickly (cognitive). Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork), egocentric (teamwork), not willing to further education (professional development). No explicit calmness under pressure, but positive atmosphere may imply.\n\nD:\n- Strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately (calmness/judgment), can concentrate very well (cognitive), solves problems extremely well (technical), takes responsibility seriously (responsibility). Weaknesses: arrogant, weak leadership (teamwork). No explicit stress handling, but ability to respond to unexpected events suggests calmness.\n\nNow we need to weigh. For long-distance flights, stress handling, calmness, reliability, decision-making, teamwork are crucial. Also professional development for long-term.\n\nCandidate B has strong stress handling, conscientiousness, weather assessment (critical for long flights). Weaknesses in teamwork (grumpy, uncooperative) could be mitigated but are concerning.\n\nCandidate D has strong problem solving, concentration, responsibility, and ability to respond to unexpected events, but weak leadership and arrogance could affect crew.\n\nCandidate C is reliable, good crew atmosphere, quick decisions, but communication difficulty and egocentric, plus lack of further education.\n\nCandidate A has anticipation and leadership but unorganized and poor at criticism.\n\nWe need to decide provisional preference. We should also consider uncertainties: we don't know severity of teamwork issues for B and D, nor calmness for D beyond \"responds adequately\". Also we don't know if A's unorganized c